<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-17T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-17T07:00:00-05:00" n="789" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d789">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Nanking Embassy Files, Lot F79, 820
                            Surplus Property: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-17T19:00:00+07:00">January
                                    17, 1946—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>38. For Ploward and Johnson from General Marshall. Agree with your
                            recommendation re Calcutta stockpile. (Re Shanghai’s No. 14 of January
                            10.) Please advise your Indian office accordingly. Question being taken
                            up with Chinese authorities in Chungking where they will be offered
                            terms you recommend and informed that quick decision necessary or
                            otherwise trucks will be disposed of to the Philippines. [Marshall.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>